00:01:39.770 --> 00:01:42.770
do we understand this phenomena,
that's actually going to be

00:01:42.770 --> 00:01:45.990
covered by the lecture today.

00:01:45.990 --> 00:01:50.180
So before we move
forward, we will

00:01:50.180 --> 00:01:51.980
have a short review
on what we have

00:01:51.980 --> 00:01:54.020
learned from the last lecture.

00:01:54.020 --> 00:01:57.980
And this is actually
what we discussed.

00:01:57.980 --> 00:02:01.450
If I have two materials,
the left-hand side

00:02:01.450 --> 00:02:05.060
and the right-hand side are two
different kinds of materials,

00:02:05.060 --> 00:02:08.250
or very thin membranes.

00:02:08.250 --> 00:02:16.120
And if I have an
incident wave coming

00:02:16.120 --> 00:02:20.300
into the boundary of these
two materials, which is just

00:02:20.300 --> 00:02:23.850
x equal to 0, as we
discussed last time,

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:27.470
basically the boundary
condition require

00:02:27.470 --> 00:02:34.760
that in order to make sure that
the membrane doesn't break,

00:02:34.760 --> 00:02:38.670
that means the k
vector, the projection

00:02:38.670 --> 00:02:43.650
in the y direction of the k
vectors has to be the same.

00:02:43.650 --> 00:02:48.740
That means the projection of the
wave in the y direction, which

00:02:48.740 --> 00:02:53.220
is along this line,
the wavelength of all

00:02:53.220 --> 00:02:58.190
the incidents refracted
and transmitted wave,

00:02:58.190 --> 00:03:01.130
the wavelengths should
be all the same.

00:03:01.130 --> 00:03:05.210
Otherwise, I can change y
and make the membrane break,

00:03:05.210 --> 00:03:07.280
or break the boundary condition.

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:08.870
So that's actually
the first thing

00:03:08.870 --> 00:03:13.070
which we learned from the
math we were doing last time.

00:03:13.070 --> 00:03:18.500
And also, the k value
are not arbitrary, right?

00:03:18.500 --> 00:03:25.140
So we were already assuming that
all three waves, all the three

00:03:25.140 --> 00:03:28.490
plane waves are oscillating
at the same frequency.

00:03:28.490 --> 00:03:30.890
If they are oscillating
at different frequencies,

00:03:30.890 --> 00:03:33.580
it doesn't work because
I can change time, then

00:03:33.580 --> 00:03:35.600
make the membranes break.

00:03:35.600 --> 00:03:38.290
So therefore, all
the three plane waves

00:03:38.290 --> 00:03:43.040
will be oscillating at the
same frequency-- omega.

00:03:43.040 --> 00:03:47.380
And according to this
formula, so we have defined

00:03:47.380 --> 00:03:50.210
and which is actually
the refraction index,

00:03:50.210 --> 00:03:53.090
which is equal to some
constant c divided

00:03:53.090 --> 00:03:58.310
by the speed of the
propagation, the phase velocity

00:03:58.310 --> 00:04:00.380
of the left-hand side material.

00:04:00.380 --> 00:04:03.340
And we also can define n
prime, which is actually

00:04:03.340 --> 00:04:09.350
equal to c, the same constant,
divided by v prime, which

00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:12.860
is the speed of propagation of
the right-hand side material.

00:04:12.860 --> 00:04:17.209
And according to the
dispersion relation,

00:04:17.209 --> 00:04:20.959
we can calculate what will
be the length of the k

00:04:20.959 --> 00:04:22.940
if omega is given.

00:04:22.940 --> 00:04:25.930
The omega for the left-hand
side and right-hand,

00:04:25.930 --> 00:04:28.620
refracted, transmitted,
and incident waves

00:04:28.620 --> 00:04:30.030
should be the same.

00:04:30.030 --> 00:04:32.500
Therefore, I can
immediately write down

00:04:32.500 --> 00:04:34.610
what would be the
length of the k vector.

00:04:34.610 --> 00:04:38.360
And that means the
length of the k vector

00:04:38.360 --> 00:04:42.350
would be equal to n
times omega over c.

00:04:42.350 --> 00:04:46.190
So c over n is actually
just v. So basically it's

00:04:46.190 --> 00:04:52.300
just the non-dispersive
median dispersion relation.

00:04:52.300 --> 00:04:54.490
And also you can go
ahead and write down

00:04:54.490 --> 00:04:56.530
what would be the
length of the k prime.

00:04:56.530 --> 00:05:02.030
And that is actually determined
by n prime omega over c.

00:05:02.030 --> 00:05:06.755
So based on these two
interesting formations,

00:05:06.755 --> 00:05:12.890
what we can conclude is that
that means k prime and kr

00:05:12.890 --> 00:05:14.930
cannot be arbitrary.

00:05:14.930 --> 00:05:19.670
They have to be aligned to
form a specific pattern.

00:05:19.670 --> 00:05:21.800
The pattern is
that the projection

00:05:21.800 --> 00:05:24.940
in the right direction
should be the same.

00:05:24.940 --> 00:05:29.680
And also at the same time,
the length of the k vector

00:05:29.680 --> 00:05:34.450
is determined by the
refraction index.

00:05:34.450 --> 00:05:38.560
So once we fix all that
and put them all together,

00:05:38.560 --> 00:05:42.410
we can conclude that based
on the projection in the y

00:05:42.410 --> 00:05:45.500
direction, we will
conclude that theta

00:05:45.500 --> 00:05:49.780
will be equal to theta r, where
theta is actually that incident

00:05:49.780 --> 00:05:54.160
angle and theta r is the
refraction angle, which

00:05:54.160 --> 00:05:58.060
is describing the direction
of the refractive wave.

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:01.210
And also the second very
interesting information

00:06:01.210 --> 00:06:06.010
we learned is that based
on the boundary condition,

00:06:06.010 --> 00:06:11.140
we can conclude n sine theta
will be equal to n prime sine

00:06:11.140 --> 00:06:12.700
theta prime.

00:06:12.700 --> 00:06:15.610
So that's actually Snell's
law, which some of you

00:06:15.610 --> 00:06:17.680
actually learned from
the high school days

00:06:17.680 --> 00:06:21.640
or from the earlier
lectures in physics.

00:06:21.640 --> 00:06:27.280
And these two
interesting results

00:06:27.280 --> 00:06:32.760
form the basis of
geometrical optics or laws.

00:06:32.760 --> 00:06:35.380
That's two of the
most important laws we

00:06:35.380 --> 00:06:38.230
learn from geometrical optics.

00:06:38.230 --> 00:06:43.000
So that actually gives
you some examples

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:45.970
and gives you some
more feeling about what

00:06:45.970 --> 00:06:47.650
we are talking about.

00:06:47.650 --> 00:06:50.650
So what we are talking about
is that if I have an incident

00:06:50.650 --> 00:06:59.410
wave coming into this boundary,
and that incident angle is

00:06:59.410 --> 00:07:04.900
theta 1, what I would expect
based on what we have just

00:07:04.900 --> 00:07:10.690
derived is that theta
r, the refracted wave

00:07:10.690 --> 00:07:15.080
direction, the
refractive wave angle,

00:07:15.080 --> 00:07:18.160
the refraction angle would be
equal to the incident angle,

00:07:18.160 --> 00:07:20.710
according to what we
have just derived.

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:24.280
I was just rotating
this by 90 degrees.

00:07:24.280 --> 00:07:28.870
And also we can calculate
what will be theta 2 according

00:07:28.870 --> 00:07:30.170
to Snell's law--

00:07:30.170 --> 00:07:34.200
n1 sine theta 1 equal
to n2 sine theta 2.

00:07:34.200 --> 00:07:40.240
And if I continue and
propagate the incident wave,

00:07:40.240 --> 00:07:44.275
here I assume that n2 is larger.

00:07:50.260 --> 00:07:52.210
If you have a larger
refraction index,

00:07:52.210 --> 00:07:57.340
that means the speed of
propagation is smaller.

00:07:57.340 --> 00:08:01.870
Larger n value give you a
smaller speed of propagation.

00:08:01.870 --> 00:08:06.430
Therefore, you can see that the
wavefront, which is actually

00:08:06.430 --> 00:08:08.990
the position of
the peak, actually

00:08:08.990 --> 00:08:14.020
got delayed compared to
the original projection.

00:08:14.020 --> 00:08:17.550
And you can see that the
red line is actually really

00:08:17.550 --> 00:08:20.990
what you would see
in the second median.

00:08:20.990 --> 00:08:23.170
And then we can also
continue to propagate

00:08:23.170 --> 00:08:25.600
and you will see
that, interesting,

00:08:25.600 --> 00:08:32.049
that means the plane wave
would change direction because

00:08:32.049 --> 00:08:34.409
of the matching
boundary condition,

00:08:34.409 --> 00:08:36.520
the membranes doesn't break.

00:08:36.520 --> 00:08:39.730
You can see that
the peak position

00:08:39.730 --> 00:08:44.260
match from the median number
1 and median number 2.

00:08:44.260 --> 00:08:49.810
The peak position, which is the
position of the line, match.

00:08:49.810 --> 00:08:55.490
And also, due to the slower
speed of propagation,

00:08:55.490 --> 00:08:57.700
the plane wave actually
change direction.

00:08:57.700 --> 00:09:00.316
So that's actually
how we can understand

00:09:00.316 --> 00:09:06.410
the mathematical result
which we derived last time

00:09:06.410 --> 00:09:09.970
by this interesting example.

00:09:09.970 --> 00:09:13.150
So that's considered
a situation which

00:09:13.150 --> 00:09:17.000
is maybe a little bit
interesting to you.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.430
So what will happen
if I now shoot light

00:09:21.430 --> 00:09:26.260
from inside some material which
delay the light slightly--

00:09:26.260 --> 00:09:30.250
for example, n1 is equal to 1.5.

00:09:30.250 --> 00:09:35.290
I shoot something
through the material,

00:09:35.290 --> 00:09:39.830
and then the second material I
have has higher speed of light,

00:09:39.830 --> 00:09:42.340
which is actually having
the speed of light

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:46.720
equal to light in a vacuum case.

00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:51.890
So in this example, I
have n1 equal to n2.

00:09:51.890 --> 00:09:59.920
Since n1 sine theta 1 is
equal to n2 sine theta 2,

00:09:59.920 --> 00:10:03.240
so now I can calculate what
will be the resulting theta

00:10:03.240 --> 00:10:05.710
2 according to this equation.

00:10:05.710 --> 00:10:09.340
So the resulting theta 2
will be sine theta 2 will

00:10:09.340 --> 00:10:15.610
be equal to n1 over
n2 sine theta 1.

00:10:15.610 --> 00:10:19.600
In this case, n1 is
greater than n2, therefore,

00:10:19.600 --> 00:10:21.440
this term is greater than 1.

00:10:24.250 --> 00:10:29.830
In this case, actually,
this ratio is equal to 1.5.

00:10:29.830 --> 00:10:31.480
So this is actually
pretty interesting.

00:10:31.480 --> 00:10:36.910
That means this factor is
actually greater than 1.

00:10:36.910 --> 00:10:41.770
I have sine theta 1, which
is multiplied in this vector.

00:10:41.770 --> 00:10:48.530
So that means if I increase
theta 1, if I increase

00:10:48.530 --> 00:10:52.630
theta 1, at some
point I will not

00:10:52.630 --> 00:10:56.170
be able to get theta
2 because theta 2 will

00:10:56.170 --> 00:11:01.680
be arcsine 1.5 sine 1.

00:11:01.680 --> 00:11:07.540
And at some point, 1.5 sine
theta 1 will be greater than 1,

00:11:07.540 --> 00:11:09.880
then I don't have
a theta 2, which

00:11:09.880 --> 00:11:12.300
can satisfy this equation.

00:11:12.300 --> 00:11:15.090
So what will happen?

00:11:15.090 --> 00:11:19.340
Maybe the whole system
explodes, I don't know.

00:11:19.340 --> 00:11:23.350
So we are going to do
a simple experiment

00:11:23.350 --> 00:11:25.370
to see what is going to happen.

00:11:25.370 --> 00:11:30.310
So before we do this kind
of dangerous experiment,

00:11:30.310 --> 00:11:37.480
