So what is going to happen is
that as a function of the time

00:37:13.980 --> 00:37:18.510
the direction of
the electric field

00:37:18.510 --> 00:37:23.680
is going to rotate as
a function of time.

00:37:23.680 --> 00:37:30.750
So we call this situation
circularly polarized.

00:37:35.120 --> 00:37:41.090
By the way, because of
the initial two components

00:37:41.090 --> 00:37:47.520
I put in, both of them
have amplitude E0.

00:37:47.520 --> 00:37:50.170
Therefore, it's
circularly polarized.

00:37:53.080 --> 00:37:56.440
I can also try to do
something different.

00:37:56.440 --> 00:38:02.400
For example, I can
change the x direction.

00:38:02.400 --> 00:38:04.800
So the third situation
is that I can

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:13.680
change the first x direction
amplitude from E0 to E0 over 2.

00:38:13.680 --> 00:38:16.560
Then what I'm going to get
is something like this.

00:38:23.370 --> 00:38:27.960
The only thing which I
change with respect to 2

00:38:27.960 --> 00:38:33.690
is that I changed the
amplitude of the electric field

00:38:33.690 --> 00:38:38.700
in the x direction
by a factor of 2.

00:38:41.490 --> 00:38:43.680
Can somebody
actually tell me what

00:38:43.680 --> 00:38:46.360
is going to happen
in this situation?

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:49.000
What will happen to the locus?

00:38:49.000 --> 00:38:50.013
AUDIENCE: Gets squished.

00:38:50.013 --> 00:38:52.430
YEN-JIE LEE: Yeah,
it gets squished in,

00:38:52.430 --> 00:38:54.460
so in the x direction.

00:38:54.460 --> 00:38:56.460
Yeah, that's right, very good.

00:38:56.460 --> 00:39:02.790
So what you are going to get
is that instead of a circle

00:39:02.790 --> 00:39:04.920
you get something like this.

00:39:04.920 --> 00:39:08.480
So this is the x direction
and this is the y direction.

00:39:08.480 --> 00:39:15.510
And this will give you a
maxima x equal to E0 over 2.

00:39:15.510 --> 00:39:21.300
And of course the original
amplitude in the y direction

00:39:21.300 --> 00:39:25.200
didn't change, and that gives
you a maximum value of E0.

00:39:25.200 --> 00:39:31.370
And this becomes an
elliptically polarized wave.

00:39:33.990 --> 00:39:42.795
So this kind of situation is
called elliptically polarized.

00:39:47.450 --> 00:39:52.100
How do we actually
visualize this situation?

00:39:52.100 --> 00:39:56.240
So that means, as
in the beginning,

00:39:56.240 --> 00:40:01.170
when the electric field is
aligned with the x-axis,

00:40:01.170 --> 00:40:03.670
it's pointing in the x-axis.

00:40:03.670 --> 00:40:07.490
It has a shorter length.

00:40:07.490 --> 00:40:12.620
And when it rotate, rotate as a
function of time to the y-axis,

00:40:12.620 --> 00:40:15.260
the amplitude becomes bigger.

00:40:15.260 --> 00:40:19.670
And it gets smaller
again, and increase again,

00:40:19.670 --> 00:40:20.830
it becomes bigger.

00:40:20.830 --> 00:40:24.080
So you can see the
amplitude is actually

00:40:24.080 --> 00:40:27.620
changing as a function of time.

00:40:27.620 --> 00:40:31.220
When you have this
kind of situation,

00:40:31.220 --> 00:40:35.210
they have different amplitudes,
although they have a fixed

00:40:35.210 --> 00:40:39.850
phase difference, so pi over 2.

00:40:39.850 --> 00:40:40.920
Any questions so far?

00:40:44.890 --> 00:40:51.560
OK, so if you noticed
that there's actually

00:40:51.560 --> 00:40:57.910
another way to produce
elliptically polarized wave.

00:40:57.910 --> 00:41:04.630
What we could do is that
instead of changing the phase

00:41:04.630 --> 00:41:13.380
by a factor of pi over 2, we
can change the phase difference.

00:41:13.380 --> 00:41:15.770
The phase difference
can be delta

00:41:15.770 --> 00:41:18.910
phi, which is the
phase difference,

00:41:18.910 --> 00:41:22.750
can be a different value,
arbitrary value, not equal

00:41:22.750 --> 00:41:27.700
to pi over 2 or 3 pi over 2.

00:41:27.700 --> 00:41:40.520
If the delta phi, which is
the phase difference between x

00:41:40.520 --> 00:41:44.705
and the y direction, EM waves--

00:41:49.720 --> 00:41:50.590
electric field.

00:41:54.910 --> 00:42:02.420
If the phase difference is not
pi over 2 or not 2 pi over 2,

00:42:02.420 --> 00:42:07.070
then you can also create an
elliptically polarized wave.

00:42:07.070 --> 00:42:14.160
So that starts from
the original figure,

00:42:14.160 --> 00:42:16.640
which we actually discussed--

00:42:16.640 --> 00:42:18.860
situation number 1.

00:42:18.860 --> 00:42:23.100
Situation number 1,
I have delta phi,

00:42:23.100 --> 00:42:26.750
the phase difference equal to 0.

00:42:26.750 --> 00:42:32.450
When that happened, you have
a linearly polarized wave.

00:42:35.690 --> 00:42:37.580
Basically what you
are going to get

00:42:37.580 --> 00:42:45.440
is a line in this
two-dimensional space.

00:42:45.440 --> 00:42:50.100
If I increase, so now
I slightly delayed.

00:42:50.100 --> 00:42:57.440
If I slightly delay the electric
field in the y direction.

00:42:57.440 --> 00:43:00.750
So if I slightly delay electric
field it in the y direction

00:43:00.750 --> 00:43:05.180
so that delta phi now is greater
than 1, what is going to happen

00:43:05.180 --> 00:43:11.560
is that it's going
to look like this.

00:43:11.560 --> 00:43:16.340
This means that they will
not reach maxima really

00:43:16.340 --> 00:43:17.860
simultaneously.

00:43:17.860 --> 00:43:20.540
There will be because
of the phase difference.

00:43:20.540 --> 00:43:23.800
And you'll see that
originally when

00:43:23.800 --> 00:43:25.910
there were no phase
difference, you

00:43:25.910 --> 00:43:30.320
would be oscillating back
and forth in this blue line.

00:43:30.320 --> 00:43:33.720
When you increase the
delta phi slightly,

00:43:33.720 --> 00:43:38.380
then you are going to get
also a elliptical shape,

00:43:38.380 --> 00:43:43.560
but now is tilted with
some degree, which

00:43:43.560 --> 00:43:48.950
is 45 degree in this case.

00:43:48.950 --> 00:43:52.630
So therefore you can
see that now I can also

00:43:52.630 --> 00:43:57.980
create this is also
elliptically polarized wave,

00:43:57.980 --> 00:44:01.100
I can also create
elliptically polarized wave

00:44:01.100 --> 00:44:05.930
by adding two components, which
they have some slight phase

00:44:05.930 --> 00:44:06.950
difference.

00:44:10.600 --> 00:44:16.690
So that is actually how I
can create a something which

00:44:16.690 --> 00:44:22.620
is called circularly polarized
or elliptically polarized.

00:44:22.620 --> 00:44:25.940
Originally before you
come into this class,

00:44:25.940 --> 00:44:28.640
it may look really
completely bizarre

00:44:28.640 --> 00:44:32.225
that, oh, I can have
electric field going up

00:44:32.225 --> 00:44:33.890
and down as a function of time.

00:44:33.890 --> 00:44:36.990
But how could I rotate
this thing, right?

00:44:36.990 --> 00:44:38.180
Looks really strange.

00:44:38.180 --> 00:44:41.300
How can I see this from
the Maxwell's equation?

00:44:41.300 --> 00:44:43.390
But now you get the idea.

00:44:43.390 --> 00:44:48.639
Basically, that's because I
can now overlap two components.

00:44:48.639 --> 00:44:54.890
Both components individually
are linearly polarized.

00:44:54.890 --> 00:44:57.140
But if I introduce
a phase difference,

00:44:57.140 --> 00:45:00.190
then the superposition
of these two components

00:45:00.190 --> 00:45:02.240
become something
which is actually

00:45:02.240 --> 00:45:03.870
rotating as a function of time.

00:45:03.870 --> 00:45:06.380
And that's pretty interesting.

00:45:06.380 --> 00:45:10.200
So let's visualize what
we have learned so far.

00:45:10.200 --> 00:45:12.710
The first one is
linearly polarized.

00:45:12.710 --> 00:45:14.270
Actually, it doesn't
surprise you--

00:45:14.270 --> 00:45:16.550
that's the example
which we have been

00:45:16.550 --> 00:45:20.300
using in the previous lectures.

00:45:20.300 --> 00:45:24.740
And this is the situation of
circularly polarized wave.

00:45:24.740 --> 00:45:33.740
So let's focus on the
figure at z equal to 0.

00:45:33.740 --> 00:45:38.900
So you can see that in
this case the direction

00:45:38.900 --> 00:45:40.550
of the electric
field is actually

00:45:40.550 --> 00:45:43.530
rotating as a function of time.

00:45:43.530 --> 00:45:47.600
And of course as we
discussed, I can actually

00:45:47.600 --> 00:45:50.990
add two electric fields
with different amplitudes

00:45:50.990 --> 00:45:55.220
or introduce slightly
different phase,

00:45:55.220 --> 00:45:59.360
then you will see that not only
that the direction is changing,

00:45:59.360 --> 00:46:02.500
but also the
amplitude is changing.

00:46:02.500 --> 00:46:09.550
And in this case we call it
elliptically polarized wave.

00:46:09.550 --> 00:46:13.030
Any questions so far?

00:46:13.030 --> 00:46:13.716
Yes?

00:46:13.716 --> 00:46:18.380
AUDIENCE: So the magnitude
always is constant with time

00:46:18.380 --> 00:46:19.314
now?

00:46:19.314 --> 00:46:24.640
YEN-JIE LEE: Yes,
so the magnitude,

00:46:24.640 --> 00:46:28.131
or say the intensity, is
proportional to E squared,

00:46:28.131 --> 00:46:28.630
right?

00:46:28.630 --> 00:46:30.085
So it's actually a constant.

00:46:34.540 --> 00:46:40.030
So now let me add
more excitement here.

00:46:40.030 --> 00:46:46.930
So now suppose I have a
perfect conductor, all right.

00:46:46.930 --> 00:46:49.060
So what I am going
to do is that I'm

00:46:49.060 --> 00:46:53.710
going to introduce some
more excitement by shooting

00:46:53.710 --> 00:46:58.780
this linearly polarized
wave through some material.

00:46:58.780 --> 00:47:04.930
If I have a perfect conductor
where all those strips,

00:47:04.930 --> 00:47:09.110
I have only strips of perfect
conductor instead of a plate--

00:47:09.110 --> 00:47:11.830
we were talking
about plate before.

00:47:11.830 --> 00:47:15.250
And the lesson we
learned is that the plate

00:47:15.250 --> 00:47:18.430
is going to refract the
electromagnetic wave

00:47:18.430 --> 00:47:22.240
because that electrons
on the plate is so busy,

00:47:22.240 --> 00:47:26.080
it's trying to make sure
that the electric field

00:47:26.080 --> 00:47:29.530
in the surface of the
plate is equal to 0

00:47:29.530 --> 00:47:32.240
because that all those electrons
are really moving around.

00:47:32.240 --> 00:47:34.900
So that's making sure the
electric field is canceled.

00:47:34.900 --> 00:47:37.700
And therefore, it's
going to refract

00:47:37.700 --> 00:47:40.060
the electromagnetic wave.

00:47:40.060 --> 00:47:45.670
So how about I
restrict the direction

00:47:45.670 --> 00:47:50.350
of the movement of the electron
so that it can only move

00:47:50.350 --> 00:47:55.870
in the horizontal direction?

00:47:55.870 --> 00:48:01.040
What is going to happen
is that in this case,

00:48:01.040 --> 00:48:06.730
the electric field is actually
oscillating up and down.

00:48:06.730 --> 00:48:09.550
And the electrons see this
field and they will say,

00:48:09.550 --> 00:48:11.730
no, no, no, this
is not why we work.

00:48:11.730 --> 00:48:14.710
This is not we are
going to vote for.

00:48:14.710 --> 00:48:18.720
And I'm going to rearrange
ourselves to compensate that,

00:48:18.720 --> 00:48:20.670
all right.

00:48:20.670 --> 00:48:22.860
And they were
asking, can I move.

00:48:22.860 --> 00:48:26.270
Oh yes, I can move in
the horizontal direction.

00:48:26.270 --> 00:48:28.660
So they jump up and down,
then they can actually

00:48:28.660 --> 00:48:33.100
cancel this electric field.

00:48:33.100 --> 00:48:36.010
Therefore, what
is going to happen

00:48:36.010 --> 00:48:38.170
when we have this
perfect conductor is

00:48:38.170 --> 00:48:42.370
that the electromagnetic field
is going to be bounced back

00:48:42.370 --> 00:48:46.900
like what we had before when
we talked about a metal plate,

00:48:46.900 --> 00:48:47.680
all right.

00:48:47.680 --> 00:48:52.210
So that's actually pretty nice.

00:48:52.210 --> 00:48:56.870
Now suppose I have
another perfect conductor.

00:48:59.520 --> 00:49:04.460
If I have another
perfect conductor,

00:49:04.460 --> 00:49:08.680
this time the perfect
conductor is arranged such

00:49:08.680 --> 00:49:14.560
that all those charges can
only move inside or outside

00:49:14.560 --> 00:49:19.310
of the board instead
of going up and down.

00:49:19.310 --> 00:49:25.210
Now I have the incident wave,
which is actually polarized

00:49:25.210 --> 00:49:29.140
in the horizontal direction.

00:49:29.140 --> 00:49:31.210
So you can see that
this time the electrons

00:49:31.210 --> 00:49:34.010
are really nervous about this.

00:49:34.010 --> 00:49:35.810
And oh no, I have
to do something,

00:49:35.810 --> 00:49:39.070
but they cannot
move up and down.

00:49:39.070 --> 00:49:40.540
Therefore, what
is going to happen

00:49:40.540 --> 00:49:45.430
is that there will be no
cancellation of electric field

00:49:45.430 --> 00:49:47.200
at this boundary.

00:49:47.200 --> 00:49:51.400
And this polarized
wave can pass through

00:49:51.400 --> 00:49:57.300
this so-called polarizer
or perfect conductor

00:49:57.300 --> 00:50:03.520
without getting stopped
or get refracted.

00:50:03.520 --> 00:50:09.130
And as you can see that
in these two examples,

00:50:09.130 --> 00:50:13.250
I have so called the easy axis.

00:50:13.250 --> 00:50:17.680
So you can see that the
easy axis, as the name

00:50:17.680 --> 00:50:21.820
should tell you, so easy axis
is the axis which is easy.

00:50:25.360 --> 00:50:26.890
All right, so what
does that mean?

00:50:26.890 --> 00:50:31.540
That means if I have
electric field aligned

00:50:31.540 --> 00:50:37.230
with the easy axis,
it will pass through.

00:50:37.230 --> 00:50:42.480
And the easy axis is
perpendicular to the direction

00:50:42.480 --> 00:50:48.540
of all those streets I have
in the perfect conductor.

00:50:48.540 --> 00:50:51.370
Let's look at the first example.

00:50:51.370 --> 00:50:54.990
It tells you that the
electric field is not

00:50:54.990 --> 00:50:56.430
aligned with the easy axis.

00:50:56.430 --> 00:51:00.590
That means it's
not easy, so it got

00:51:00.590 --> 00:51:03.270
refracted-- oh, life is hard.

00:51:03.270 --> 00:51:08.110
And the second electric
field is smarter.

00:51:08.110 --> 00:51:10.770
It got aligned
with the easy axis.

00:51:10.770 --> 00:51:13.230
So life is easy,
it passed through.

00:51:13.230 --> 00:51:18.310
That's how I remember
this so-called easy axis.

00:51:18.310 --> 00:51:19.362
Any questions?

00:51:24.820 --> 00:51:29.770
So we have been talking
about all those crazy names

00:51:29.770 --> 00:51:33.310
of polarized light.

00:51:33.310 --> 00:51:39.610
And I hope that you also have
learned about unpolarized light

00:51:39.610 --> 00:51:40.510
before.

00:51:40.510 --> 00:51:43.120
Most of the lights
are unpolarized.

00:51:43.120 --> 00:51:46.735
For example, light emitted
from those light bulbs

00:51:46.735 --> 00:51:51.670
are not polarized because
every emission of a photon

00:51:51.670 --> 00:51:55.330
can be aligned in
different direction.

00:51:55.330 --> 00:51:57.760
Therefore, as I
was talking about,

00:51:57.760 --> 00:52:00.150
there are an infinite number
of photons hitting my face

00:52:00.150 --> 00:52:01.950
and bouncing back to your eye.

00:52:01.950 --> 00:52:05.930
All those things are not
aligned to the same direction

00:52:05.930 --> 00:52:09.010
as what we have been
discussing before.

00:52:09.010 --> 00:52:13.610
In the case of linearly
polarized wave,

00:52:13.610 --> 00:52:16.930
all the electric fields are
pointing to the same direction.

00:52:16.930 --> 00:52:22.540
And apparently those lights
hitting my face is not aligned

00:52:22.540 --> 00:52:25.840
and it's actually pointing
to random directions.

00:52:25.840 --> 00:52:32.530
So that brings me to the
fifth situation, which

00:52:32.530 --> 00:52:34.630
I would like to talk about.

00:52:34.630 --> 00:52:47.800
The fifth situation is that I
could have unpolarized light.

00:52:47.800 --> 00:52:50.890
So what do I mean by
unpolarized light?

00:52:50.890 --> 00:52:54.340
That means electromagnetic
waves which

00:52:54.340 --> 00:52:59.780
were produced independently
by a large number

00:52:59.780 --> 00:53:03.850
of uncorrelated source.

00:53:03.850 --> 00:53:05.750
You may ask, OK,
wait, wait, wait--

00:53:05.750 --> 00:53:09.500
unpolarized means that we have
a lot of different light source

00:53:09.500 --> 00:53:11.060
pointing to different angles.

00:53:11.060 --> 00:53:13.700
Shouldn't it just
look like this?

00:53:13.700 --> 00:53:16.880
So you have pointing this
direction, all the directions,

00:53:16.880 --> 00:53:20.150
all the possible
directions, pointing

00:53:20.150 --> 00:53:24.130
to all different possible
directions, like this.

00:53:24.130 --> 00:53:29.530
Shouldn't that diagram
actually tell you

00:53:29.530 --> 00:53:33.690
something about
unpolarized light?

00:53:33.690 --> 00:53:35.310
Life is hard.

00:53:35.310 --> 00:53:38.670
If everything is
aligned and also

00:53:38.670 --> 00:53:44.350
arriving at the same time like
this, what is going to happen?

00:53:44.350 --> 00:53:46.660
They cancel, right?

00:53:46.660 --> 00:53:48.660
Because all those
things are vectors.

00:53:48.660 --> 00:53:51.890
If they reach maxima
at the same time,

00:53:51.890 --> 00:53:53.825
this means that they
are emitting always

00:53:53.825 --> 00:53:56.950
at the same time, but
in random direction.

00:53:56.950 --> 00:54:01.690
And emitting at the
same wavelength,

00:54:01.690 --> 00:54:04.030
then they are going
to cancel each other.

00:54:04.030 --> 00:54:08.560
So apparently that's not what
I mean by unpolarized light.

00:54:08.560 --> 00:54:12.670
What I mean is that
they can be pointing

00:54:12.670 --> 00:54:15.750
to different directions,
but that emission

00:54:15.750 --> 00:54:20.860
time and the wavelength of all
those emitted electromagnetic

00:54:20.860 --> 00:54:24.070
waves can be slightly
different, otherwise they

00:54:24.070 --> 00:54:29.330
will just cancel each
other completely.

00:54:29.330 --> 00:54:31.440
Any questions about
what I just said?

00:54:34.800 --> 00:54:36.240
So very good.

