01:08:05.820 --> 01:08:09.490
just one, and then the second
one, and the third one--

01:08:09.490 --> 01:08:15.340
and have then pass through
some imaginary polarizer.

01:08:15.340 --> 01:08:17.979
So let's suppose
I have unpolarized

01:08:17.979 --> 01:08:21.880
light with intensity at 0.

01:08:21.880 --> 01:08:25.010
So basically, after it
passed through this polarizer

01:08:25.010 --> 01:08:27.910
with a axis pointing
to the x direction,

01:08:27.910 --> 01:08:29.810
in this case the x
direction is pointing

01:08:29.810 --> 01:08:33.460
to this direction, what
you are going to get

01:08:33.460 --> 01:08:37.149
is that you are going
to filter from all

01:08:37.149 --> 01:08:40.270
those unpolarized
direction, you are

01:08:40.270 --> 01:08:46.300
going to filter only the light
which is actually parallel

01:08:46.300 --> 01:08:48.220
to the easy axis.

01:08:48.220 --> 01:08:52.630
So therefore, after the
unpolarized light source

01:08:52.630 --> 01:08:55.060
passes through
this polarizer, you

01:08:55.060 --> 01:08:57.460
are going to have all
the electric field

01:08:57.460 --> 01:09:01.160
pointing to the x direction.

01:09:01.160 --> 01:09:02.840
Now everybody can accept.

01:09:02.840 --> 01:09:05.140
And of course if I have
a second one, which

01:09:05.140 --> 01:09:07.939
is in the y direction,
since there will

01:09:07.939 --> 01:09:10.720
be no component pointing
to the y direction,

01:09:10.720 --> 01:09:14.100
you get zero electric field.

01:09:14.100 --> 01:09:16.359
That's very nice.

01:09:16.359 --> 01:09:18.540
So Einstein was
really happy that, oh,

01:09:18.540 --> 01:09:23.920
that means unpolarized
light maybe is just 50%

01:09:23.920 --> 01:09:27.160
of the polarized light
in the x direction

01:09:27.160 --> 01:09:30.660
and 50% of the polarized
light in the y direction.

01:09:30.660 --> 01:09:42.170
Because each time I emit one
photon, the first half of them

01:09:42.170 --> 01:09:48.970
